  "prompt": "What is a good amount of money yearly to live more than comfortably in the USA?",
  "response": "The amount of money needed to live more than comfortably in the USA can vary significantly depending on several factors, including location, lifestyle, family size, and personal preferences. However, here are some general guidelines:\n\n1. **Cost of Living**: Major metropolitan areas (like New York City, San Francisco, or Los Angeles) often have a higher cost of living, where living \"comfortably\" might require an income of $100,000 or more per year for an individual or around $200,000 for a family. In contrast, smaller cities or rural areas might allow for a comfortable lifestyle with $60,000 to $80,000 a year.\n\n2. **Family Size**: A larger family requires more income to cover housing, food, healthcare, and education costs.\n\n3. **Lifestyle Choices**: This includes expenses like dining out, travel, hobbies, entertainment, and savings. If you prefer a lavish lifestyle with frequent vacations and luxury purchases, you'll need a higher income.\n\n4. **Savings and Investments**: Living comfortably often includes the ability to save for retirement, education, and emergencies. Generally, experts recommend saving at least 15% of your income.\n\nAs a rough estimate, for a comfortable lifestyle in many parts of the U.S., an annual income of:\n\n- **$75,000 to $100,000** for individuals\n- **$150,000 to $200,000** for families\n\ncan be considered a good benchmark. Ultimately, the best approach is to evaluate your specific needs, location, and financial goals to determine what \"comfortably\" means for you.",
